※※
# scaffold-sky-workflow

Manually-run meta-workflow that authors a brand-new `.sky` workflow from a
plain-English brief, then lints it until it passes. Two stages:

  author  — writes .sky/workflows/<name>.sky from {{request}}, following the bundled sky-workflow-authoring skill
  lint    — runs `sky lint` on the new file and fixes every error, looping until lint is clean (max 6 passes)

Run it:

  sky run scaffold-sky-workflow --var name="deploy-on-tag" --var request="on a GitHub release, run the deploy script and post the result to Slack"

  - name    kebab-case filename + workflow name for the generated file (no .sky extension)
  - request what the workflow should do, in plain English

Output: .sky/workflows/<name>.sky, lint-clean and ready to run.

Required skill — install before first run (no marketplace plugin needed):

  sky examples install sky-workflow-authoring

The skill resolves from .claude/skills/sky-workflow-authoring/SKILL.md in the
target repo or ~/.claude and is injected into both nodes' system prompts.
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "scaffold-sky-workflow"
description = "Author a new .sky workflow from a plain-English brief and lint it until clean. Fire via: sky run scaffold-sky-workflow --var name=<file> --var request=<what it should do>"
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 2.00
⊕⊕

※※
Step 1 — author. Writes the new workflow file from the brief, following the
bundled sky-workflow-authoring skill (four delimiters, valid trigger, node DAG,
correct variable references). Does not lint yet — that's the next stage.
※※

§author§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
§§

∆author∆
Author a new Skylence `.sky` workflow at .sky/workflows/{{name}}.sky.

What it must do: {{request}}

Follow the sky-workflow-authoring skill exactly: the four Unicode delimiter blocks (⊕meta⊕, §id§, ∆id∆, ※※), `name = "{{name}}"` matching the filename, exactly one trigger, and a sensible node DAG. Pick node types (claude / bash / script / http / loop) that fit the brief; keep prompts terse. Create the .sky/workflows/ directory if absent. Write the file — do not lint it yet.
∆∆

※※
Step 2 — lint. A loop node: each pass reads the file the author wrote, runs
`sky lint`, and fixes every reported error. The loop.until.bash condition
re-runs this node until lint exits 0 (max 6 passes). Loop nodes can't chain a
session, so the prompt reads the file fresh each pass.
※※

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
depends_on = ["author"]
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \".sky/workflows/$SKY_NAME.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Read .sky/workflows/{{name}}.sky, then run `sky lint .sky/workflows/{{name}}.sky` and read its output. Fix every reported error and warning in the file, using the sky-workflow-authoring skill's error-code table (SKY-WF-*) to map each code to its fix. Common ones: quote the RHS of `when`; add `chain_from` targets to `depends_on`; quote `$SKY_*` in bash; declare every env-var reference in the `secrets` array. Re-run lint after editing. This node loops until lint passes — make concrete fixes each pass. When clean, output the final lint result and the file path.
∆∆
